<subSubSection id="C32ADAB5FFF00F55FAF9F4C8C8DEFECE" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="186" pageId="2" pageNumber="185" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8F893EFFF00F55FAF9F4C8C8DEFECE" blockId="2.[1384,2591,2778,3129]" lastBlockId="3.[788,1382,292,719]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="186" pageId="2" pageNumber="185">
<emphasis id="B944552CFFF00F54FAF9F4C8CA15F43B" bold="true" box="[1385,1632,2935,2968]" pageId="2" pageNumber="185">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 142-153 mm, tail 153-195 mm; weight 87-101 g. Dorsal fur of 
<taxonomicName id="4C30F2BDFFF00F54FA7FF421CA12F41C" box="[1519,1639,2974,3007]" class="Mammalia" family="Nesomyidae" genus="Eliurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="2" pageNumber="185" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="antsingy">Antsingy</taxonomicName>
Tufted-tail Rat is generally drab dark brown or gray-brown, and undercoat fur is nearly black. Ventral pelage varies and is often entirely white, sometimes mottled gray-white. Last one-half of tail has brown or grayish brown hair and, in some individuals, mixed with white hair. Tail ends with well-defined tuft, and some individuals have consecutive white and brown whorls. Tarsi, feet, and toes are white.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="DF4FD9B6FFF00F54FFFFF328C445F234" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6600516" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6600516" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6600516/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="185" startId="2.[111,143,3223,3244]" targetBox="[15,2746,12,3644]" targetPageId="1">
<paragraph id="8B8F893EFFF00F54FFFFF328C445F234" blockId="2.[110,2587,3220,3484]" pageId="2" pageNumber="185">
